{
  "answer": "Both poems concern grief's meaning, but their rhetorical arcs run in opposite directions.\n\n**The Wanderer** (Old English Elegies, chapter 11) moves from particular lament to universal homiletic through a three-stage structure:\n1. A third-person frame narrator opens the poem by introducing the lone-dweller seeking mercy on the 'rime-cold sea' — one man, one winter, one loss.\n2. The wanderer's first-person voice then unfolds his specific grief: the dead lord/gold-friend, the hall he can never return to, the hallucinatory dream of clasping his liege-lord that dissolves into fallow waves. At the emotional climax, the voice pivots outward into the 'ubi sunt' meditation — 'Where has the horse gone? Where has the warrior gone?' — generalising one man's loss into all earthly decay.\n3. The frame narrator reclaims the poem for a closing Christian homily: 'Good is he who keeps his faith... Well is it for him who seeks grace, comfort from the Father in heaven.' Philosophy/wisdom arrives only AFTER the emotional experience has been fully rendered. The arc is: Pathos (particular exile grief) → Logos (universal meditation on transience) → Ethos (Christian moral counsel).\n\nThe rhetorical method is inductive: suffering generates wisdom. The frame structure (third-person narrator → first-person wanderer → third-person narrator) creates controlled distance, so that when the homiletic conclusion comes, it feels earned by ordeal.\n\n**Falsafa-e-Gham** (Bang-e-Dara Part 3, chapter 7) runs the opposite direction — from philosophical proposition to particular consolation:\n1. The poem opens not with one man's grief but with universal assertion: 'Upon the waves of Sorrow, life's frail bubble rides.' Sorrow is immediately declared to be the 'spirit's light,' the 'polish for the heart's own face' — a philosophical thesis, not a lament.\n2. A negative proof follows: the person who has never wept, never known heartbreak, is spiritually blind — 'the secret of all life is veiled and hidden far away.' The argument is built logically, not emotionally.\n3. The philosophical argument deepens: Love is eternal; when the beloved dies, love persists as sorrow. 'Love does not perish when the one beloved has passed away / It lives within the soul as Sorrow.' Sorrow is redefined as love's metaphysical continuation.\n4. An extended river parable — stream shattering on valley rocks and reforming into silver thread — illustrates the metaphysics of separation and reunion as emotional illustration of the prior philosophical point.\n5. The poem closes with consolation that the departed 'shine' like stars in darkness — not a religious command but an affective culmination of the argument.\n\nThe arc is deductive: Logos (universal claim about sorrow) → Logos (negative proof, love-as-sorrow argument) → Pathos (river parable) → Pathos (consolation). The question is posed implicitly by the title ('what is the philosophy of grief?') and the poem answers it systematically.\n\n**Structural contrast**: The Wanderer withholds its wisdom until grief has been lived through; wisdom is the reward of suffering. Falsafa-e-Gham begins with wisdom and uses it to reframe suffering; philosophy precedes and transforms the emotional response. In The Wanderer the homiletic 'frame' is external to the lament; in Falsafa-e-Gham the philosophy IS the lament's substance from the first line. Both arrive at consolation, but The Wanderer reaches it by ascending from personal loss to God, while Falsafa-e-Gham reaches it by descending from metaphysical principle to the grieving individual.",
